[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/cover-tree] The **cover tree** is a type of data structure in computer science that is specifically designed to facilitate the speed-up of a nearest neighbor search.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/cover-tree] It is a refinement of the Navigating Net data structure, and related to a variety of other data structures developed for indexing intrinsically low-dimensional data.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/cover-tree] The tree can be thought of as a hierarchy of levels with the top level containing the root point and the bottom level containing every point in the metric space.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/cover-tree] Each level *C* is associated with an integer value *i* that decrements by one as the tree is descended.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/cover-tree] Like other metric trees the cover tree allows for nearest neighbor searches in $O(\eta *\log {n})$ where $\eta$ is a constant associated with the dimensionality of the dataset and n is the cardinality.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/cover-tree] To compare, a basic linear search requires $O(n)$ , which is a much worse dependence on n .
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/cover-tree] However, in high-dimensional metric spaces the $\eta$ constant is non-trivial, which means it cannot be ignored in complexity analysis.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/cover-tree] Unlike other metric trees, the cover tree has a theoretical bound on its constant that is based on the dataset's expansion constant or doubling constant (in the case of approximate NN retrieval).
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/cover-tree] The bound on search time is $O(c^{12}\log {n})$ where c is the expansion constant of the dataset.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/cover-tree] Although cover trees provide faster searches than the naive approach, this advantage must be weighed with the additional cost of maintaining the data structure.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/cover-tree] In a naive approach adding a new point to the dataset is trivial because order does not need to be preserved, but in a cover tree it can take $O(c^{6}\log {n})$ time.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/cover-tree] However, this is an upper-bound, and some techniques have been implemented that seem to improve the performance in practice.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/cover-tree] The cover tree uses implicit representation to keep track of repeated points.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/fixed-radius-near-neighbors] In computational geometry, the **fixed-radius near neighbor problem** is a variant of the nearest neighbor search problem.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/fixed-radius-near-neighbors] In the fixed-radius near neighbor problem, one is given as input a set of points in *d*-dimensional Euclidean space and a fixed distance Δ.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/fixed-radius-near-neighbors] One must design a data structure that, given a query point *q*, efficiently reports the points of the data structure that are within distance Δ of *q*.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/fixed-radius-near-neighbors] The problem has long been studied; Bentley (1975) cites a 1966 paper by Levinthal that uses this technique as part of a system for visualizing molecular structures, and it has many other applications.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/fixed-radius-near-neighbors] One method for solving the problem is to round the points to an integer lattice, scaled so that the distance between grid points is the desired distance Δ.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/fixed-radius-near-neighbors] A hash table can be used to find, for each input point, the other inputs that are mapped to nearby grid points, which can then be tested for whether their unrounded positions are actually within distance Δ.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/fixed-radius-near-neighbors] The number of pairs of points tested by this procedure, and the time for the procedure, is linear in the combined input and output size when the dimension is a fixed constant.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/fixed-radius-near-neighbors] However, the constant of proportionality in the linear time bound grows exponentially as a function of the dimension.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/fixed-radius-near-neighbors] Using this method, it is possible to construct indifference graphs and unit disk graphs from geometric data in linear time.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/fixed-radius-near-neighbors] Modern parallel methods for GPU are able to efficiently compute all pairs fixed-radius NNS.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/fixed-radius-near-neighbors] For finite domains, the method of Green shows the problem can be solved by sorting on a uniform grid, finding all neighbors of all particles in O(kn) time, where k is proportional to the average number of neighbors.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/fixed-radius-near-neighbors] Hoetzlein improves this further on modern hardware with counting sorting and atomic operations.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/fixed-radius-near-neighbors] The fixed-radius near neighbors problem arises in continuous Lagrangian simulations (such as smoothed particle hydrodynamics), computational geometry, and point cloud problems (surface reconstructions).
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] The goal of supervised learning (more specifically classification) is to learn a decision rule that can categorize data instances into pre-defined classes.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] The *k*-nearest neighbor rule assumes a *training* data set of labeled instances (i.e. the classes are known).
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] It classifies a new data instance with the class obtained from the majority vote of the k closest (labeled) training instances.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] Closeness is measured with a pre-defined metric.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] Large margin nearest neighbors is an algorithm that learns this global (pseudo-)metric in a supervised fashion to improve the classification accuracy of the *k*-nearest neighbor rule.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] The main intuition behind LMNN is to learn a pseudometric under which all data instances in the training set are surrounded by at least k instances that share the same class label.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] If this is achieved, the leave-one-out error (a special case of cross validation) is minimized.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] For $d(\cdot ,\cdot )$ to be well defined, the matrix $\mathbf {M}$ needs to be positive semi-definite.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] The Euclidean metric is a special case, where $\mathbf {M}$ is the identity matrix.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] This generalization is often (falsely) referred to as Mahalanobis metric.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] Figure 1 illustrates the effect of the metric under varying $\mathbf {M}$ .
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] The two circles show the set of points with equal distance to the center ${\vec {x}}_{i}$ .
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] In the Euclidean case this set is a circle, whereas under the modified (Mahalanobis) metric it becomes an ellipsoid.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] The algorithm distinguishes between two types of special data points: *target neighbors* and *impostors*.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] Target neighbors are selected before learning.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] Each instance ${\vec {x}}_{i}$ has exactly k different target neighbors within D , which all share the same class label $y_{i}$ .
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] The target neighbors are the data points that *should become* nearest neighbors *under the learned metric*.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] Let us denote the set of target neighbors for a data point ${\vec {x}}_{i}$ as $N_{i}$ .
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] An impostor of a data point ${\vec {x}}_{i}$ is another data point ${\vec {x}}_{j}$ with a different class label (i.e. $y_{i}\neq y_{j}$ ) which is one of the nearest neighbors of ${\vec {x}}_{i}$ .
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] During learning the algorithm tries to minimize the number of impostors for all data instances in the training set.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] Large margin nearest neighbors optimizes the matrix $\mathbf {M}$ with the help of semidefinite programming.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] The objective is twofold: For every data point ${\vec {x}}_{i}$ , the *target neighbors* should be *close* and the *impostors* should be *far away*.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] Figure 1 shows the effect of such an optimization on an illustrative example.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] The learned metric causes the input vector ${\vec {x}}_{i}$ to be surrounded by training instances of the same class.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] If it was a test point, it would be classified correctly under the $k=3$ nearest neighbor rule.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] The second goal is achieved by penalizing distances to impostors ${\vec {x}}_{l}$ that are less than one unit further away than target neighbors ${\vec {x}}_{j}$ (and therefore pushing them out of the local neighborhood of ${\vec {x}}_{i}$ ).
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] With a hinge loss function ${\textstyle [\cdot ]_{+}=\max(\cdot ,0)}$ , which ensures that impostor proximity is not penalized when outside the margin.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] The margin of exactly one unit fixes the scale of the matrix M .
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] Any alternative choice $c>0$ would result in a rescaling of M by a factor of $1/c$ .
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] The hyperparameter ${\textstyle \lambda >0}$ is some positive constant (typically set through cross-validation).
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] Here the variables $\xi _{ijl}$ (together with two types of constraints) replace the term in the cost function.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] They play a role similar to slack variables to absorb the extent of violations of the impostor constraints.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] The last constraint ensures that $\mathbf {M}$ is positive semi-definite.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] The optimization problem is an instance of semidefinite programming (SDP).
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] Although SDPs tend to suffer from high computational complexity, this particular SDP instance can be solved very efficiently due to the underlying geometric properties of the problem.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] In particular, most impostor constraints are naturally satisfied and do not need to be enforced during runtime (i.e. the set of variables $\xi _{ijl}$ is sparse).
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] A particularly well suited solver technique is the working set method, which keeps a small set of constraints that are actively enforced and monitors the remaining (likely satisfied) constraints only occasionally to ensure correctness.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] LMNN was extended to multiple local metrics in the 2008 paper.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] This extension significantly improves the classification error, but involves a more expensive optimization problem.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] In their 2009 publication in the Journal of Machine Learning Research, Weinberger and Saul derive an efficient solver for the semi-definite program.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] It can learn a metric for the MNIST handwritten digit data set in several hours, involving billions of pairwise constraints.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] An open source Matlab implementation is freely available at the authors web page.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/large-margin-nearest-neighbor] Kumal et al. extended the algorithm to incorporate local invariances to multivariate polynomial transformations and improved regularization.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] Formally, the nearest neighbor (NN) search problem is defined as follows: given a set S of points in a space M and a query point $q\in M$ , find the closest point in S to q.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] Donald Knuth in volume 3 of *The Art of Computer Programming* (1973) called it the **post-office problem**, referring to an application of assigning to a residence the nearest post office.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] A direct generalization of this problem is a k-NN search, where we need to find the k closest points.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] Most commonly M is a metric space and dissimilarity is expressed as a distance metric, which is symmetric and satisfies the triangle inequality.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] Even more common, M is taken to be the d-dimensional vector space where dissimilarity is measured using the Euclidean distance, Manhattan distance or other distance metric.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] However, the dissimilarity function can be arbitrary.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] One example is asymmetric Bregman divergence, for which the triangle inequality does not hold.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] Various solutions to the NNS problem have been proposed.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] The quality and usefulness of the algorithms are determined by the time complexity of queries as well as the space complexity of any search data structures that must be maintained.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] The informal observation usually referred to as the curse of dimensionality states that there is no general-purpose exact solution for NNS in high-dimensional Euclidean space using polynomial preprocessing and polylogarithmic search time.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] The simplest solution to the NNS problem is to compute the distance from the query point to every other point in the database, keeping track of the "best so far".
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] This algorithm, sometimes referred to as the naive approach, has a running time of *O*(*dN*), where *N* is the cardinality of *S* and *d* is the dimensionality of *S*.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] There are no search data structures to maintain, so the linear search has no space complexity beyond the storage of the database.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] Naive search can, on average, outperform space partitioning approaches on higher dimensional spaces.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] The absolute distance is not required for distance comparison, only the relative distance.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] In geometric coordinate systems the distance calculation can be sped up considerably by omitting the square root calculation from the distance calculation between two coordinates.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] The distance comparison will still yield identical results.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] Since the 1970s, the branch and bound methodology has been applied to the problem.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] In the case of Euclidean space, this approach encompasses spatial index or spatial access methods.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] Several space-partitioning methods have been developed for solving the NNS problem.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] Perhaps the simplest is the k-d tree, which iteratively bisects the search space into two regions containing half of the points of the parent region.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] Queries are performed via traversal of the tree from the root to a leaf by evaluating the query point at each split.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] Depending on the distance specified in the query, neighboring branches that might contain hits may also need to be evaluated.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] R-trees can yield nearest neighbors not only for Euclidean distance, but can also be used with other distances.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] In the case of general metric space, the branch-and-bound approach is known as the metric tree approach.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] Particular examples include vp-tree and BK-tree methods.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] Using a set of points taken from a 3-dimensional space and put into a BSP tree, and given a query point taken from the same space, a possible solution to the problem of finding the nearest point-cloud point to the query point is given in the following description of an algorithm.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] (Strictly speaking, no such point may exist, because it may not be unique.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] This may not be the case, but it is a good heuristic.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] After having recursively gone through all the trouble of solving the problem for the guessed half-space, now compare the distance returned by this result with the shortest distance from the query point to the partitioning plane.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] This latter distance is that between the query point and the closest possible point that could exist in the half-space not searched.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] If this distance is greater than that returned in the earlier result, then clearly there is no need to search the other half-space.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] If there is such a need, then you must go through the trouble of solving the problem for the other half space, and then compare its result to the former result, and then return the proper result.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] An approximate nearest neighbor search algorithm is allowed to return points whose distance from the query is at most c times the distance from the query to its nearest points.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] The appeal of this approach is that, in many cases, an approximate nearest neighbor is almost as good as the exact one.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] In particular, if the distance measure accurately captures the notion of user quality, then small differences in the distance should not matter.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] Proximity graph methods (such as navigable small world graphs and HNSW) are considered the current state-of-the-art for the approximate nearest neighbors search.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] The methods are based on greedy traversing in proximity neighborhood graphs $G(V,E)$ in which every point $x_{i}\in S$ is uniquely associated with vertex $v_{i}\in V$ .
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] The search for the nearest neighbors to a query *q* in the set *S* takes the form of searching for the vertex in the graph $G(V,E)$ .
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] The basic algorithm – greedy search – works as follows: search starts from an enter-point vertex $v_{i}\in V$ by computing the distances from the query q to each vertex of its neighborhood $\{v_{j}:(v_{i},v_{j})\in E\}$ , and then finds a vertex with the minimal distance value.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] If the distance value between the query and the selected vertex is smaller than the one between the query and the current element, then the algorithm moves to the selected vertex, and it becomes new enter-point.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] The algorithm stops when it reaches a local minimum: a vertex whose neighborhood does not contain a vertex that is closer to the query than the vertex itself.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] These works were preceded by a pioneering paper by Toussaint, in which he introduced the concept of a *relative neighborhood* graph.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] Locality sensitive hashing (LSH) is a technique for grouping points in space into 'buckets' based on some distance metric operating on the points.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] Points that are close to each other under the chosen metric are mapped to the same bucket with high probability.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] The cover tree has a theoretical bound that is based on the dataset's doubling constant.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] The bound on search time is *O*(*c*12 log *n*) where *c* is the expansion constant of the dataset.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] In the special case where the data is a dense 3D map of geometric points, the projection geometry of the sensing technique can be used to dramatically simplify the search problem.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] This approach requires that the 3D data is organized by a projection to a two-dimensional grid and assumes that the data is spatially smooth across neighboring grid cells with the exception of object boundaries.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] These assumptions are valid when dealing with 3D sensor data in applications such as surveying, robotics and stereo vision but may not hold for unorganized data in general.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] In practice this technique has an average search time of *O*(*1*) or *O*(*K*) for the *k*-nearest neighbor problem when applied to real world stereo vision data.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] In high-dimensional spaces, tree indexing structures become useless because an increasing percentage of the nodes need to be examined anyway.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] To speed up linear search, a compressed version of the feature vectors stored in RAM is used to prefilter the datasets in a first run.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] The final candidates are determined in a second stage using the uncompressed data from the disk for distance calculation.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] The VA-file approach is a special case of a compression based search, where each feature component is compressed uniformly and independently.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] The optimal compression technique in multidimensional spaces is Vector Quantization (VQ), implemented through clustering.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] The database is clustered and the most "promising" clusters are retrieved.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] Huge gains over VA-File, tree-based indexes and sequential scan have been observed.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] Also note the parallels between clustering and LSH.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] There are numerous variants of the NNS problem and the two most well-known are the *k*-nearest neighbor search and the ε-approximate nearest neighbor search.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] In some applications it may be acceptable to retrieve a "good guess" of the nearest neighbor.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] In those cases, we can use an algorithm which doesn't guarantee to return the actual nearest neighbor in every case, in return for improved speed or memory savings.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] Often such an algorithm will find the nearest neighbor in a majority of cases, but this depends strongly on the dataset being queried.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] Algorithms that support the approximate nearest neighbor search include locality-sensitive hashing, best bin first and balanced box-decomposition tree based search.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] Nearest neighbor distance ratio does not apply the threshold on the direct distance from the original point to the challenger neighbor but on a ratio of it depending on the distance to the previous neighbor.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] It is used in CBIR to retrieve pictures through a "query by example" using the similarity between local features.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] More generally it is involved in several matching problems.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] Fixed-radius near neighbors is the problem where one wants to efficiently find all points given in Euclidean space within a given fixed distance from a specified point.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] The distance is assumed to be fixed, but the query point is arbitrary.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] For some applications (e.g. entropy estimation), we may have *N* data-points and wish to know which is the nearest neighbor *for every one of those N points*.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] This could, of course, be achieved by running a nearest-neighbor search once for every point, but an improved strategy would be an algorithm that exploits the information redundancy between these *N* queries to produce a more efficient search.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] As a simple example: when we find the distance from point *X* to point *Y*, that also tells us the distance from point *Y* to point *X*, so the same calculation can be reused in two different queries.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/nearest-neighbor-search] Given a fixed dimension, a semi-definite positive norm (thereby including every Lp norm), and *n* points in this space, the nearest neighbour of every point can be found in *O*(*n* log *n*) time and the *m* nearest neighbours of every point can be found in *O*(*mn* log *n*) time.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/vantage-point-tree] By recursively applying this procedure to partition the data into smaller and smaller sets, a tree data structure is created where neighbors in the tree are likely to be neighbors in the space.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/vantage-point-tree] One generalization is called a **multi-vantage-point tree** (or **MVP tree**): a data structure for indexing objects from large metric spaces for similarity search queries.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/vantage-point-tree] It uses more than one point to partition each level.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/vantage-point-tree] Peter Yianilos claimed that the vantage-point tree was discovered independently by him (Peter Yianilos) and by Jeffrey Uhlmann.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/vantage-point-tree] Yet, Uhlmann published this method before Yianilos in 1991.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/vantage-point-tree] Uhlmann called the data structure a metric tree, the name VP-tree was proposed by Yianilos.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/vantage-point-tree] Vantage-point trees have been generalized to non-metric spaces using Bregman divergence by Nielsen et al.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/vantage-point-tree] This iterative partitioning process is similar to that of a *k*-d tree, but uses circular (or spherical, hyperspherical, etc.) rather than rectilinear partitions.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/vantage-point-tree] In two-dimensional Euclidean space, this can be visualized as a series of circles segregating the data.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/vantage-point-tree] The vantage-point tree is particularly useful in dividing data in a non-standard metric space into a metric tree.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/vantage-point-tree] The way a vantage-point tree stores data can be represented by a circle.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/vantage-point-tree] First, understand that each node of this tree contains an input point and a radius.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/vantage-point-tree] All the left children of a given node are the points inside the circle and all the right children of a given node are outside of the circle.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/vantage-point-tree] The tree itself does not need to know any other information about what is being stored.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/vantage-point-tree] All it needs is the distance function that satisfies the properties of the metric space.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/vantage-point-tree] A vantage-point tree can be used to find the nearest neighbor of a point *x*.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/vantage-point-tree] At any given step we are working with a node of the tree that has a vantage point *v* and a threshold distance *t*.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/vantage-point-tree] The point of interest *x* will be some distance from the vantage point *v*.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/vantage-point-tree] If the recursive use of the algorithm finds a neighboring point *n* with distance to *x* that is less than |*t* − *d*| then it cannot help to search the other subtree of this node; the discovered node *n* is returned.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/vantage-point-tree] Otherwise, the other subtree also needs to be searched recursively.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/vantage-point-tree] A similar approach works for finding the *k* nearest neighbors of a point *x*.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/vantage-point-tree] In the recursion, the other subtree is searched for *k* − *k′* nearest neighbors of the point *x* whenever only *k′* (< *k*) of the nearest neighbors found so far have distance that is less than |*t* − *d*|.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/vantage-point-tree] Updating a vantage-point tree is relatively easy compared to the FastMap approach.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/vantage-point-tree] For FastMap, after inserting or deleting data, there will come a time when FastMap will have to rescan itself.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/vantage-point-tree] That takes up too much time and it is unclear to know when the rescanning will start.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/vantage-point-tree] The time cost to build a vantage-point tree is approximately *O*(*n* log *n*).
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/vantage-point-tree] For each element, the tree is descended by log *n* levels to find its placement.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/vantage-point-tree] However there is a constant factor *k* where *k* is the number of vantage points per tree node.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/vantage-point-tree] The time cost to search a vantage-point tree to find a single nearest neighbor is *O*(log *n*).
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/vantage-point-tree] There are log *n* levels, each involving *k* distance calculations, where *k* is the number of vantage points (elements) at that position in the tree.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/vantage-point-tree] The time cost to search a vantage-point tree for a range, which may be the most important attribute, can vary greatly depending on the specifics of the algorithm used and parameters.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/vantage-point-tree] Brin's paper gives the result of experiments with several vantage point algorithms with various parameters to investigate the cost, measured in number of distance calculations.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/vantage-point-tree] The space cost for a vantage-point tree is approximately *n*.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/vantage-point-tree] Each element is stored, and each tree element in each non-leaf node requires a pointer to its descendant nodes.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/vantage-point-tree] (See Brin for details on one implementation choice.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/vantage-point-tree] With n points there are *O*(*n*2) pairwise distances between points.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/vantage-point-tree] However, the creation of a vantage-point tree requires that only *O*(*n* log *n*) distances be calculated explicitly, and a search requires only *O*(log *n*) distance calculations.
[src:nearest-neighbor-search-nns/vantage-point-tree] For example, if x and y are points and it is known that the distance *d*(*x*, *y*) is small then any point z that is far from x will also necessarily be almost as far from y because the metric space's triangle inequality gives *d*(*y*, *z*) ≥ *d*(*x*, *z*) − *d*(*x*, *y*).
